= Names

  1. = Use PascalCase for type names.
  2. = Do not use I as a prefix for interface names.
  3. = Use PascalCase for enum values.
  4. = Use camelCase for function names.
  5. = Use camelCase for property names and local variables.
  6. = Do not use _ as a prefix for private properties.<= o:p>
  7. = Use whole words in names when possible.

Components=

  1. 1 file per logical component (e.g. parser, scanner, emitter, checker).
  2. = Do not add new files. :)
  3. = files with .generated.* suffix are auto-generated, do not hand-edit them.

Types

  1. = Do not export types/functions unless you need to share it across multiple components.
  2. = Do not introduce new types/values to the global namespace.
  3. = Shared types should be defined in types.ts.
  4. = Within a file, type definitions should come first.

null<= span style=3D'font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Segoe UI",sans-serif;mso-fareast-fon= t-family: "Times New Roman";color:#1F2328;mso-fareast-language:EN-CA'> and =

  1. = Use undefin= ed. Do not use null.<= /o:p>

General Assumpt= ions

  1. = Consider objects like Nodes, Symbols, etc. as immutable outside the component t= hat created them. Do not change them.
  2. = Consider arrays as immutable by default after creation.

Classes

  1. = For consistency, do not use classes in the core compiler pipeline. Use function closures instead.

Flags

  1. = More than 2 related Boolean properties on a type should be turned into a fl= ag.

Comments

  1. = Use JSDoc style comments for functions, interfaces, enums, and classes.

Strings

  1. = Use double quotes for strings.
  2. = All strings visible to the user need to be localized (make an entry in diagnosticMessages.json).

Diagnostic Mess= ages

  1. = Use a period at the end of a sentence.
  2. = Use indefinite articles for indefinite entities.
  3. = Definite entities should be named (this is for a variable name, type name, etc.= .).
  4. = When stating a rule, the subject should be in the singular (e.g. "An external module cannot..." instead of "External modules cannot...").
  5. = Use present tense.

Diagnostic Mess= age Codes

Diagnostics are categorized into general ranges. If adding a new diagnostic message, use the first integral number greater than the last used number in the appropriate range.

  • = 1000 range for syntactic messages
  • = 2000 for semantic messages
  • = 4000 for declaration emit messages
  • = 5000 for compiler options messages
  • = 6000 for command line compiler messages
  • = 7000 for noImplicitAny messages

General Constru= cts

For a variety of reasons, we avoid certain constructs, and use some = of our own. Among them:

  1. = Do not use for..in statements; instead, use ts.forE= ach, ts.forE= achKey and ts.forE= achValue. Be aware of their slig= htly different semantics.
  2. = Try to use ts.forEach, ts.map, and ts.filt= er instead of loops w= hen it is not strongly inconvenient.

Style

  1. = Use arrow functions over anonymous function expressions.
  2. = Only surround arrow function parameters when necessary.
    For example,     (x) =3D> x + x is wrong but the following are corre= ct:
    • x =3D> x + x
    • (x,y) =3D> x + y
    • <T>(x: T, y: T) =3D> x =3D=3D=3D= y
  3. = Always surround loop and conditional bodies with curly braces. Statements on = the same line are allowed to omit braces.
  4. = Open curly braces always go on the same line as whatever necessitates them.=
  5. = Parenthesized constructs should have no surrounding whitespace.
    A single space follows commas, colons, and semicolons in those constru= cts. For example:
    • for (var i =3D 0, n =3D str.length; i <= ; 10; i++) { }
    • if (x < 10) { }
    • function f(x: number, y: string): void { = }
  6. = Use a single declaration per variable statement
    (i.e. use     var x =3D 1; var y =3D 2; over <= span style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Consolas;mso-fareast-font-family= :"Times New Roman"; mso-bidi-font-family:"Courier New";mso-fareast-language:EN-CA'>var x = =3D 1, y =3D 2;= ).
  7. else goes on a separate line from the clo= sing curly brace.
  8. = Use 4 spaces per indentation.

 

 

Limit the length of code to 500–600 lines in a file and the methods to 20–30 lines.

1.  Naming convention of variable/method/class names:

·     Variable Names: camelCase
Example:
firstNumber =3D 12

·     Constants: UPPER_CASE with underscore ‘_’ bet= ween multiple words
Example:
const FIRST_NUMBER =3D 18

·     Method Names: camelCase
Example:
sumOfTwoNumbers()

·     Class Names: PascalCase
Example:
export class EmployeeDetails {}

·     File Names: lower-case (Separated by ‘-’ if the na= me is of two/more words)
Example:
employee-details

3. Mention data types of variables while declaration and for method parameters.

·     Variable Type
Example:
firstNumber: number

·     Parameter Type
Example:

Data = types for method parameters

4. Avoid the use of type ‘any’. Create an interface/class instead.
Example:
Let’s assume that we need to assign the details of a person to a particu= lar variable. So, we create a variable user of type UserDetails as shown below:=
user: UserDetails

UserDetails Interface

Inter= face for UserDetails

5. Add method documentation&= nbsp;for methods as well as parameters passed (Press /** + enter wherever method documentation needs to be added)
Example:

Method documentation

6. Keep method/variable names as informative as possible.

·     Method Name
Example:

Infor= mative method name

·     Variable Name
Example:
firstName: string

7. Use data access specifiers while declaring variables/methods (Like public/private etc)
Example:
If we declare a variable ‘firstNumber’ and it is used only inside the cl= ass say ‘Addition’, it is marked as private.
private firstNumber: number

Similarly, a method can be marked as pri= vate if it is only used inside a particular class.
private sumOfTwoNumbers(): number {}

However, If a variable is used in an HTML file, it should be marked public.

8. Use TSLint and make = sure not to disable any lint rule. TSLint extension should be enabled in order to include lint rules in the project.

9. Scope of the variabl= es should be as minimum as possible.
Example:
Since FIRST_NUMBER is used only inside the method sumOfTwoNumber, it= is initialised inside that particular method, thus limiting the scope of the variable to that particular method.

Scope= of FIRST_NUMBER

10. Avoid using repetitive if else (Use switch case instead)
Example:

Switch case

11. Use try catch to ha= ndle the error and exceptions. Make sure there is no unhandled excep= tion in your code.
Example:

Try c= atch block for error handling

12. Always log the erro= rs and relevant information. This helps in debugging the code in case of error= s. The following log levels can be used to add logging in your code:

·     Error
Example:
console.error('This is an error log')

·     Warn
Example:
console.warn('This is an warning log')

·     Info
Example:
console.info('This is an info log')

·     Debug
Example:
console.debug('This is a debug log')

·     Trace
Example:
console.trace('This is a trace log')

13. Add TODOs for pendi= ng code blocks.
Example:

TODO = for pending code block

14. Reuse the code as m= uch as possible and remove unnecessary code blocks.=

 

 

1. Overview

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      All new files in the vanilla/vanilla repo <= em>MUST be in Typescript.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      New code MUST NOT use JQuery. Instead, native browser APIs and utility functions from @core/dom may be used= .

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      All files MUST be formatted with Prettier.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Files SHOULD NOT declare more than one class in a single file.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Files with a default export MUST be named equivalently to the symbol (class, function, interface, constant) that they export.<= /span>

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Interfaces for code defined inside of Vanilla Forums code&nb= sp;MUST be named beginning with the character I (e.g., = ;ITh= ing, IBu= ttonOptions). This rule does= not apply to type definitions for dependencies.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Method names SHOULD be declared in camelCase.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Static class properties MUST be declared in all upper case with underscore separators.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Class names MUST be declared in PascalCase.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      const MUST be used where possible. Otherwise let MUST be used.&= nbsp;var=  MUST NOT be us= ed.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      =3D=3D=3D MUST be used instead of =3D=3D. An exception is made for null checks, specifically someVar =3D=3D null.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      A file MUST NOT contain unused imports.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Test files MUST be located in a directory __tests__ and end wit= h the extension .test.ts or .test.js.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      console.log and other built-in logging functions MUST NOT be used. Instead, logging functions from <= code>@co= re/utility may be used= .

1.1. Styling rules

All files MUST be formatted with Prettier. This is to ensure consistent formatting, and to prevent overly large diffs when someone else formats a file. This encompass= es all spacing and formatting rules. The following rules, among others, will a= ll be automatically enforced by formatting with Prettier:

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Code MUST use four spaces for indenting, not tabs.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Opening braces for classes and functions MUST be on the= same line.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Control structure keywords MUST have one space after them; met= hod and function calls MUST NOT.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Opening braces for control structures MUST go on the= same line, and closing braces MUST go on the next line after the body.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Opening parentheses for control structures MUST NOT have a space after them, and closing parentheses for control structures <= span style=3D'font-family:"Segoe UI",sans-serif'>MUST NOT have a space before.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Lines MUST be 120 characters or less.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Semicolons are REQUIRED.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Strings SHOULD use double quotes " or Backtick quotes \`.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Colons in object and interface declarations MUST NOT be pr= eceded by a space and M= UST be followed by a space.

<= span style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb= sp;      Object and array declarations MUST contain a trailing comma, if i= t is declared on multiple lines.

An exception is m=

contained in a directory called legacy. At some point i=

save SHOULD be

3. General



3.1. Files



<=
span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;     
All files MUST use
the Unix LF (linefeed) line ending.



<=
span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;     
All files MUST end
with a single blank line.



<=
span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;     
A file with a default export MUST be named the same as the expor=
t.



3.2. Character encoding



<=
span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;     
Code MUST use
only UTF-8 without BOM.



3.3. Indenting<=
/span>



<=
span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;     
Code MUST use
an indent of four spaces, and 



<=
span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;     
Using only spaces, and not mixing spaces with tabs, helps to
avoid problems with diffs, patches, history, and annotations.



3.4. Single and double quo=
tes



<=
span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;     
All strings will automatically have their quotes adjusted by
Prettier.



<=
span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;     
Strings SHOULD use
double quotes " or back-tick quotes `.



<=
span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;     
Strings MAY use
double quotes if there are double quotes that would have to otherwise be
escaped.



=
// Good
=
&quo=
t;Something"
=
&quo=
t;OMG she's using double quotes!"
=
`Thi=
s one uses backtick quotes and has ${num=
berOfVars} var=
iables.`
=
'&qu=
ot;Single quotes can work sometimes too!", he excaimed.'=

=
 
=

=
=
// Bad
=
'Sin=
gle quotes with no escaped characters'
=
'Def=
initely not single quotes if there\'s single quotes that need to be escaped=
.'



4. Namespaces, types, and interfaces



Namespaces



Typescript namespaces MUST
NOT be used; ES Modules MUST be used instead.



4.1. Types and Interfaces<=
o:p>



<=
span

sp;

ate).=

style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;

used instead of type literals.

=

=
 
=

=

}

Casting should generally be avoided whenever possible, but w=
hen

sp;     
When casting a type the var=
iable

used.



<=

sp;     
When casting a type the <=

6. Variables, objects & functions



6.1. Variable declarations=




<=
span
style=3D'mso-list:Ignore'>·&nb=
sp;     
const MUST be

7. Control structures



The general style rules for control structures are listed be=

<=

There MUST

<=

The closing brace MUST be
on the next line after the body



The body of each structure MUST be enclosed by braces. This
standardizes how the structures look, and reduces the likelihood of introdu=
cing
errors as new lines get added to the body.

Do's and Don'ts



General Types



Number,
String,
Boolean<=
/code>,
Symbol
and Object



❌ Don’t ever use
the types Number, String, Boolean, Symbol,
or Object These
types refer to non-primitive boxed objects that are almost never used
appropriately in JavaScript code.



/* WRONG */
function<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'> reverse(s: String=
): String=
;



✅ Do use the
types number, string, boolean,
and symbol.



/* OK */
function reverse(s: string): string;



Instead of Object,
use the non-primitive object type (added
in TypeScript 2.2).



Generics



❌ Don’t ever ha=
ve a
generic type which doesn’t use its type parameter. See more details in =
;TypeScript
FAQ page.



any



❌ Don’t use&nbs=
p;any<=
/code> as
a type unless you are in the process of migrating a JavaScript project to
TypeScript. The compiler effectively treats&n=
bsp;any<=
/code> as
“please turn off type checking for this thing”. It is similar to putting
an @ts-ignore comment
around every usage of the variable. This can be very helpful when you are f=
irst
migrating a JavaScript project to TypeScript as you can set the type for st=
uff
you haven’t migrated yet as any, but in a full
TypeScript project you are disabling type checking for any parts of your
program that use it.



In cases where you don’t know what type you want to accept, or when you =
want
to accept anything because you will be blindly passing it through without
interacting with it, you can use unknown.



Callback Types


Return Types of Callbacks



❌ Don’t use the
return type any for
callbacks whose value will be ignored:



/* WRONG */
function<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'> fn(x: () =3D> any) {<=
/span>
  x();<=
/span>
}



✅ Do use the ret=
urn
type void for
callbacks whose value will be ignored:



/* OK */
function fn(x: () =3D> void) {
  x();<=
/span>
}



❔ Why: Using&nb=
sp;void=
 is
safer because it prevents you from accidentally using the return value of&n=
bsp;x in
an unchecked way:



function fn(x: () =3D> void) {
  var k =3D x(); // oops! meant =
to do something else
  k.doSomething(); // error, but w=
ould be OK if the return type had been 'any'
}



Optional Parameters in Callbacks



❌ Don’t use
optional parameters in callbacks unless you really mean it:



/* WRONG */
interface=
 Fetcher {
  getObject(done: (data: unknown, elapsedTime?: number=
) =3D> void): void;
}



This has a very specific meaning: the done callba=
ck might
be invoked with 1 argument or might be invoked with 2 arguments. The author
probably intended to say that the callback might not care about the elapsedTime=
 parameter,
but there’s no need to make the parameter optional to accomplish this — it’s
always legal to provide a callback that accepts fewer arguments.



✅ Do write callb=
ack
parameters as non-optional:



/* OK */
interface Fetcher {
  getObject(done: (data: unknown, elapsedTime: number=
) =3D> void): void;
}



Overloads and Callbacks



❌ Don’t write
separate overloads that differ only on callback arity:



/* WRONG */
declare function<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'> beforeAll(action=
: () =3D> void, timeout?: number=
): void;
declare function<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'> beforeAll(
  action=
: (done: DoneFn=
) =3D> void,
  timeout?: number=

): void;



✅ Do write a sin=
gle
overload using the maximum arity:



/* OK */
declare function beforeAll(
  action=
: (done: DoneFn=
) =3D> void,
  timeout?: number=

): void;



❔ Why: It’s alw=
ays
legal for a callback to disregard a parameter, so there’s no need for the
shorter overload. Providing a shorter callback first allows incorrectly-typ=
ed
functions to be passed in because they match the first overload.



Function Overloads



Ordering



❌ Don’t put more
general overloads before more specific overloads:



/* WRONG */
declare function<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'> fn(x: unknown): unknown;
declare function<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'> fn(x: HTMLElement): number=
;
declare function<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'> fn(x: HTMLDivElemen=
t): string=
;
var myElem=
: HTMLDivElemen=
t;
var x =3D fn(myElem=
); // x: unknown, =
wat?



✅ Do sort overlo=
ads
by putting the more general signatures after more specific signatures:



/* OK */
declare function fn(x: HTMLDivElement): string=
;
declare function<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'> fn(x: HTMLElement): number=
;
declare function<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'> fn(x: unknown): unknown;
var myElem=
: HTMLDivElemen=
t;
var x =3D fn(myElem=
); // x: string, :=
)



❔ Why: TypeScri=
pt
chooses the first matching overload&n=
bsp;when
resolving function calls. When an earlier overload is “more general” than a
later one, the later one is effectively hidden and cannot be called.



Use Optional Parameters



❌ Don’t write
several overloads that differ only in trailing parameters:



/* WRONG */
interface=
 Example {
  diff(one: string=
): number=
;
  diff(one: string=
, two: string=
): number=
;
  diff(one: string=
, two: string=
, three<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'>: boolean): number=
;
}



✅ Do use optional
parameters whenever possible:



/* OK */
interface Example {
  diff(one: string=
, two?: string=
, three<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'>?: boolean): number=
;
}



Note that this collapsing should only occur when all overloads have the =
same
return type.



❔ Why: This is
important for two reasons.



TypeScript resolves signature compatibility by seeing if any signature of
the target can be invoked with the arguments of the source, and
extraneous arguments are allowed. This code, for example, expos=
es a
bug only when the signature is correctly written using optional parameters:=




function fn(x: (a: string, b: number, c: number) =3D> void) {}
var x: Example;
// When written=
 with overloads, OK -- used first overload
// When written=
 with optionals, correctly an error
fn(x.diff);



The second reason is when a consumer uses the “strict null checking” fea=
ture
of TypeScript. Because unspecified parameters appear as undefined in
JavaScript, it’s usually fine to pass an explicit undefined to
a function with optional arguments. This code, for example, should be OK un=
der
strict nulls:



var x: Example;
// When written with overloads, incorrect=
ly an error because of passing 'undefined' to 'string'
// When written=
 with optionals, correctly OK
x.diff("somethi=
ng", true ? undefined=
 : "hour&qu=
ot;);



Use Union Types



❌ Don’t write
overloads that differ by type in only one argument position:



/* WRONG */
interface=
 Moment=
 {
  utcOffset(): number=
;
  utcOffset(b: number=
): Moment=
;
  utcOffset(b: string=
): Moment=
;
}



✅ Do use union t=
ypes
whenever possible:



/* OK */

  utcOffset(): number=
;
  utcOffset(b: number=
 | string=
): Moment=
;
}



Note that we didn’t make b optional here
because the return types of the signatures differ.



❔ Why: This is
important for people who are “passing through” a value to your function:



function fn(x: string): Moment;
function fn(x: number): Moment;
function<=
span
style=3D'font-size:11.5pt;font-family:Consolas;color:black'> fn(x: number=
 | string=
) {<=
/span>
  // When written=
 with separate overloads, incorrectly an error
  // When written=
 with union types, correctly OK
  return=
 moment=
().utcOffset(x);
}



 



 



2.
Use of comments :



Avoid unnecessary comments. Start writ=
ing
self-explanatory code that eliminates the need for excessive comments.=




//Using excessive comments

function calculate(r: number<=
span

  // Calculate the area of a circle

  const x =3D Math.PI * Math.pow(r, 2);

console.=

In the above example, since the variab=

Now, let’s check the improved version =

  const area =3D Math.PI * Math.pow(radius, 2);

  return area;

}

4. SOLID principles



Implementing SOLID principles in your
codebase will definitely make your codebase cleaner and much better. It
consists of five principles which helps in code maintainability, scalability
and robustness.






Image f=
rom https://devopedia.org/solid-design=
-principles



a) SRP (Single Responsibilty Principle=
): As the name suggests it says each class or module should have=
 a
single responsibility or reason to change. It helps keep classes focused and
manageable. If a class has multiple responsibilities, consider separating t=
hose
responsibilities into distinct classes. This promotes better code organizat=
ion
and reduces the impact of changes.

  private employeeId: number;

  private salary: number;



  constructor(name: string, employeeId: number, sal=
ary: number) {

    =

    =

  // getters and setters for employee information

g {

    =
return this<=
/span>.name;

  }

ring): void {

    =
this.name =3D name;

  }

 number {

    =
return this<=
/span>.employeeId;

  }



  setEmployeeId(em=
ployeeId: number): void {

    =
this.employeeId =3D employeeId;

  }



  getSalary(): num=
ber {

    =
return this<=
/span>.salary;

  }



  setSalary(salary=
: number): void {

    =
this.salary =3D salary;

  }



}

b)&nb=
sp;Open-Closed Principle (OCP): Software
entities (classes, modules, functions) should be open for extension but clo=

for modification. This principle promotes using abstractions and interfaces=

c) Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)=
: Subtypes must be substitutable for their base types. It ensur=
es

/span>: string;

printPersonInfo(te=
acher);



d) Interface Segregation Principle (IS=
P): Clients should not be forced to depend on interfaces they do =
not
use which means that interfaces should be specific to the needs of the clie=
nts.
Instead of having a single large interface, create smaller, focused interfa=
ces
that represent specific sets of behaviors. This allows clients to depend on=
ly
on the interfaces they require, reducing coupling and promoting flexibility=
.



interface Shape {

  calculateArea():=
 number;

}



interface Circle extends Shape {

  radius: number;<=
/span>

}



interface Rectangle extends Shape {

  height: number;<=
/span>

  width: number;

}



class CircleShape implements Circle {

  radius: number;<=
/span>



  constructor(radius: number) {

    =
this.radius =3D radius;

  }



  calculateArea():=
 number {

    =
return Math.PI * this.radius * this.radius;

  }

}



class RectangleShape implements Rectangle {

  height: number;<=
/span>

  width: number;



  constructor(height: number, width: number) {

    =
this.height =3D height;

    =
this.width =3D width;

  }



  calculateArea():=
 number {

    =
return this<=
/span>.height * this.width;

  }

}



e) Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP=
): The DIP states that high-level modules/classes should not dep=
end
on low-level modules/classes directly. Instead, they should depend on
abstractions. By depending on abstractions (interfaces or abstract classes)
rather than concrete implementations, you decouple components, promote
modularity, and facilitate easier testing and maintainability.



interface Vehicle {

  start(): <=
span
class=3Dhljs-builtin>void;

}



class Car implements Vehicle {

  start(): <=
span
class=3Dhljs-builtin>void {

    console.log("Starting the car...");

  }

}



class Motorcycle implements Vehicle {

  start(): <=
span
class=3Dhljs-builtin>void {

    console.log("Starting the motorcycle...");

  }

}



class VehicleService {

  private vehicle: Vehicle;



  constructor(vehicle: Vehicle) {

    this.vehicle =3D vehicle;
  }



  public startVehicle(): <=
/span>void {

    this.vehicle.start();

  }

}



const car =3D new Car();

const motorcycle =
=3D new Motorcycle();



const vehicleServ=
ice1 =3D new VehicleService(car);

vehicleService1.st=
artVehicle(); 

// Output =3D "Starting the car..."=




const vehicleServ=
ice2 =3D new VehicleService(motorcycle);

vehicleService2.st=
artVehicle(); 

// Output =3D "Starting the motorcycle..."=
